711803f-a.text:
West 25th Street -- East from No 267

West 25th Street, east from (No. 267), a point east of Eighth Ave. The 12 and 16 story buildings facing each other, this side of 7th Ave. are respectively, the Graphic Arts Building and the National Cloak and Suit Company. No. 2 of this set shows the West Side Lumber Company at No. 223-243. Adjacent to same is a clearance where a row of 3 story structures stood which bore No's 219-231.

March 21, 1938.

P.L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.

According to the New York Sun of September 22, 1938, a six-story apartment house is to be erected on the site shown in the picture (219-229 West 25th Street). This building will be erected at a cost of $175,000. It will have a base 126x38.7 and will contain a total of 171 rooms, with eleven apartments on a floor.

710127f-a.text:
306-314 Eight Avenue, east side, between W 25th and 26th Streets, showing Miner's Theatre. This structure, originally built in 1881, was rebuilt in 1904 after a fire the preceeding year. In 1913 it closed, to be later reopened as the Chelsea(Movie Theatre).
1910
International News Photo

710128f-a.text:
Eighth avenue, east side, from West 25th (right, not seen) to 26th Streets, showing at No. 312 the Chelsea Theatre. This structure, prior to 1913 was formerly Miner's Tneatre which opened here in 1881. It burned in 1903 and was rebuilt in 1904. A photogrpah of 1910 (q.v.) closely compared, will indicate
the present building minus the marquee.
View 1: June 25, 1928
View 2: March 21, 1938
P. L. Sperr
